{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E2M82Vk57YdFs3SxgwWN6F","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the LEVEL-DEFS and KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does this require multiple modules interacting? Yes — the AI vision model needs to classify the image, and then the pipeline needs to route it to \"held for review\" rather than \"published\". The failure mode could be: (a) the AI model doesn't classify correctly, or (b) the routing logic fails. The core question is whether the AI correctly classifies the image.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: The behavior hinges on what the real AI vision model actually produces — I can't mock that without just asserting the mock works, which defeats the purpose of testing. The classification step is the critical dependency here.\n- MULTI-STEP: Image classification feeds into a routing decision, but it's fundamentally a single agentic step where the model makes the judgment call.\n\nThis lands at **Agentic** level because the behavior's correctness depends entirely on the real AI vision model's output.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfusc**\n\nThe text classifier needs to handle obfuscated hate speech, and I can't mock that away — the real model has to actually recognize the obfuscated patterns. Testing with a mock would just verify the mock's predefined response, not whether the real model handles obfuscation correctly. This is also **Agentic**.\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\nThis one's different — it's about routing logic. If I mock both AI models to return \"clean\", I can actually test whether the system publishes the post correctly. The failure mode here lives in the decision logic, not in the AI models themselves.\n\nThe behavior assumes the AI models have already made their decision, so the real question is whether the system correctly publishes rather than holds or silently drops after both checks pass. I think I can catch this with mocked models at Integration level, since the bug would be in the routing logic. But there's a wrinkle — I also need to verify the system doesn't silently drop posts, which might require more careful testing.\n\nFor the performance requirement, mocking the AI models would hide the real latency problem since mocks return instantly. The 5-second SLA depends on actual model execution time, so this needs to run at Agentic level with real or realistic AI latency to be meaningful.\n\nFor the unavailability scenario, I need to distinguish between simulating an API error response versus testing the actual queuing and retry logic. The core question is whether the system correctly routes to a retry queue when the vision model fails, which could be tested by injecting an error response from the AI service.\n\nFor Behavior 6, I'm now considering whether the consistency of moderation decisions depends on the LLM's inherent behavior or on the system's caching and deduplication logic.\n\nThe real issue here is that a borderline image might get different moderation results from the LLM on successive calls due to the model's non-determinism. If I mock the LLM, it'll always return the same answer, so the test won't actually catch real inconsistency issues. I need the real model to verify that the system handles borderline cases consistently across multiple submissions.\n\nSince the test involves submitting the same image multiple times and comparing results across full pipeline runs, this is workflow-level testing, but the core dependency on LLM non-determinism pushes the minimum requirement to agentic-level testing.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the test levels for each behavior: explicit content detection and obfuscated hate speech both need real AI models (agentic), a post passing both checks is more about routing logic (integration), the 5-second performance requirement spans the full pipeline with real calls (workflow), error handling and retry queuing don't need real AI (integration), and the borderline consistency check requires multiple pipeline runs with real models (workflow).\n\nFor the behavior about posts passing both checks, I need to think through whether that actually requires real AI models to verify the \"passing\" classification, or if mocking would suffice.  The key failure mode is that a clean post gets held or dropped instead of published, so I'm really testing the routing decision logic—mocking the AI to return \"clean\" results lets me verify the system publishes correctly, which makes this integration-level. For the retry queuing, a production system likely uses something like Redis or Kafka rather than in-memory storage, so that's also integration-level.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9459,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9459},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c41735a-0da1-46f9-b0e4-9264503f48c7","uuid":"1574439d-253b-4f2a-8759-b2ace7447ced"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E2M82Vk57YdFs3SxgwWN6F","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XBnS3F4gzzWATqx5cAhqB2","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The routing logic (flag → hold) is simple enough to test in isolation, but the failure mode here is whether the real AI vision model actually classifies explicit content correctly — not just whether the routing code handles a flagged result. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the vision model always passes because the mock returns whatever the test author tells it to; it proves nothing about the model's classification ability. LLM-DEP: Correctness depends entirely on what the real AI vision model produces for explicit images. The test must submit a real explicit image to the real model to catch a real failure.","test_description":"Submit a curated set of known-explicit test images (pre-approved for testing) to the real AI vision model via the moderation pipeline. Assert that the pipeline response status is 'held_for_review' (not 'published') for every image in the set. Also assert that no explicit image reaches a published state in the datastore.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The obfuscation-resistance property is a quality of the real AI text model's classification capability, not of any routing or wiring logic. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock of the text classifier that returns 'hate_speech' for obfuscated input has pre-encoded the answer; it tests nothing about the model's robustness. LLM-DEP: Whether 'h4te spe3ch' or unicode-substituted variants are correctly classified as hate speech is a non-deterministic, model-quality question that only the real AI text model can answer. A test using mocks would always pass regardless of model regression.","test_description":"Build a fixture of obfuscated hate speech variants (letter substitution, unicode lookalikes, zero-width characters, homoglyphs) for a fixed set of seed phrases. Submit each variant through the real text moderation endpoint. Assert that every variant returns a flagged/held status, and that none reach a published state.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here is in the routing and publish logic — that after both image and text classifiers return 'clean', the system correctly transitions to 'published' rather than getting stuck, held by default, or silently discarded. This is a module-boundary failure between the classification output, decision logic, and publish sink. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking both classifiers to return 'clean' is valid here because the behavior under test is the downstream routing and publish path, not the classifiers themselves. LLM-DEP: No — the behavior explicitly conditions on both checks passing; the AI model's judgment is out of scope. The wiring between classifier output and publish state is deterministic integration logic.","test_description":"Wire the image classifier and text classifier with test doubles that always return 'clean'. Submit a benign post through the full moderation pipeline. Assert that the post's final state in the datastore is 'published', that no human-review queue entry exists for it, and that the submission response indicates success.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the AI models eliminates the dominant latency contributors; a test with mocks would pass the 5-second SLA trivially, even if the real system consistently exceeds it. REAL-INFRA: Real network latency to the AI APIs is a primary variable. LLM-DEP: Real AI API call time is non-deterministic and is exactly what this SLA guards against. MULTI-STEP: The 5-second budget covers the full sequential pipeline — image check AND text check AND publish decision — which constitutes multiple real agentic steps. A single-step Agentic test cannot cover the cumulative latency of both steps plus orchestration overhead.","test_description":"Submit a batch of posts (with both image and text content) through the live moderation pipeline using real AI model endpoints. Record wall-clock time from submission to final state transition for each post. Assert that p99 latency across the batch is under 5 seconds. Run at least 20 posts to get a meaningful latency distribution.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the interaction between the error-handling path of the image classifier client and the retry queue module — this is a real module-boundary failure. When the classifier throws a connection/timeout error, does the caller enqueue the post or fall through to auto-approve? This only manifests when both modules interact. REAL-INFRA: The retry queue likely uses a real local queue backend (Redis, DB, in-process). LLM-DEP: No — the AI model is explicitly unavailable; its output is irrelevant. Simulating unavailability with a stub that raises a network error is correct and does not hide the failure. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the queue would hide whether the enqueue call is actually made and persisted; use a real (local) queue backend.","test_description":"Configure the image classifier client to raise a connection error (using patch.object on the HTTP client's send method). Submit an image post through the moderation pipeline. Assert that: (1) the post is NOT marked as published or auto-approved, (2) a retry queue entry exists for the post with its original payload, and (3) no human-review flag is raised as a substitute for the missing classification.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"LLM-DEP: This behavior exists precisely because AI models can be non-deterministic on borderline inputs. A mock always returns the same answer and would always pass, proving nothing. The real failure is a real AI model returning different classifications across calls. MULTI-STEP: The test must run the full pipeline multiple times (multiple submissions → multiple real AI calls → multiple routing decisions) and compare outcomes across those runs. This is multiple agentic steps in sequence/parallel, placing it firmly at Workflow. MOCK-HIDE: Any level below Workflow hides the exact failure the behavior is designed to catch.","test_description":"Select a curated set of pre-identified borderline test images. For each image, submit it through the full live moderation pipeline N times (e.g., N=5) in rapid succession. Assert that all N pipeline runs for each image produce the same final decision ('held' or 'published'). A disagreement across runs for any single image is a test failure. Document the images and acceptance threshold (e.g., must be consistent across all 5 runs).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9459,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9459},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c41735a-0da1-46f9-b0e4-9264503f48c7","uuid":"d9c4e2da-1aca-4207-91cd-45b88b5e45a1"}
